02:25.500 --> 02:28.668
Boston
Legal Season 05 Episode 10
“Thanksgiving”

02:28.950 --> 02:30.440
What do you mean,
you've got plans?

02:30.480 --> 02:31.650
You said you were going out of town.

02:31.690 --> 02:34.440
–I said I might go out of town, but—
–Didn't invite me, did you?

02:34.480 --> 02:38.040
Because I never made o-official plans.

02:38.810 --> 02:41.210
Who are you spending
Thanksgiving with?

02:41.250 --> 02:43.480
A friend. Uh, you wouldn't like him.

02:43.520 --> 02:45.470
Who?

02:45.670 --> 02:46.710
–It's personal.
–Personal?

02:46.750 --> 02:49.430
Well, you could come to. I'll ask him.

02:49.440 --> 02:52.090
Who?

02:53.400 --> 02:57.040
Technically, it would be…

02:57.340 --> 03:00.210
Melvin Palmer.

03:00.510 --> 03:02.260
–You must be joking.
–He's a good guy.

03:02.300 --> 03:05.330
You're spending Thanksgiving
with Melvin Palmer?

03:05.370 --> 03:06.330
He's a hoot.

03:06.340 --> 03:07.780
No, y-you're putting me on.

03:07.820 --> 03:10.650
Well, I had no place else
to go, and he called and—

03:10.690 --> 03:12.980
When did you become
friends with that bobo-head?

03:13.020 --> 03:14.420
When he saved our asses.

03:14.460 --> 03:18.470
–He did not save our asses.
–He saved our asses in Utah.

03:22.830 --> 03:24.120
Are you being serious?

03:24.160 --> 03:25.160
He's a decent guy.

03:25.200 --> 03:27.420
No, he is not.
He's nothing of the sort.

03:27.460 --> 03:30.496
–Look—
–And you're not having dinner with him.

03:30.700 --> 03:32.420
We'll find somewhere else to go.

03:32.460 --> 03:36.700
But you will not —will not— be
spending Thanksgiving with that vile—

03:36.740 --> 03:38.100
–I like him.
–I don't care.

03:38.140 --> 03:41.020
No, forget it. No.

03:42.090 --> 03:45.880
No. Nope.

03:50.920 --> 03:52.060
Mugged?

03:52.070 --> 03:54.070
You should've seen
the size of the knife.

03:54.110 --> 03:55.770
–Are you okay?
–No, I'm fine.

03:55.810 --> 03:57.740
I-I just can't believe it happened.

03:57.780 --> 03:59.010
Shirley, you have to tell the police.

03:59.050 --> 04:00.080
No, I don't want to do that.

04:00.120 --> 04:01.990
Shirley, it was an
attempted armed robbery.

04:02.030 --> 04:03.680
Well, he's 9 years old, Carl.

04:03.720 --> 04:06.920
Oh, my God. Now the
homecoming is complete.

04:06.930 --> 04:08.540
Carl Sack, how are you,
my friend?

04:08.580 --> 04:10.540
Never liked you, but what
the hey? I can be courteous.

04:10.580 --> 04:12.250
Shirl, hi, doll. Sorry I'm late.

04:12.290 --> 04:15.788
I hit some traffic, not to
mention a few pedestrians.

04:16.690 --> 04:18.410
Just mowed?'em right—
I can see I've lost you.

04:18.450 --> 04:22.420
Shirley, I don't know what to
say other than I'm so sorry.

04:22.430 --> 04:24.990
Edwin, how long
have you had that boy?

04:25.010 --> 04:27.290
Six months. I've enrolled him in
finishing school, not to worry.

04:27.330 --> 04:29.430
What the hell is this?

04:29.450 --> 04:31.920
You've sued me already?

04:31.930 --> 04:33.010
–Did you read it?
–Why would I?

04:33.050 --> 04:35.480
It's marked “privileged
and confidential.”

04:35.520 --> 04:39.810
Edwin, it was hand-delivered to you
because you were meant to read it.

04:39.850 --> 04:42.460
Ah, well, that's different.

04:44.100 --> 04:45.400
What does it say?

04:45.420 --> 04:47.340
It says the firm is going broke.

04:47.380 --> 04:52.200
Funny. Love her. She's just—
The firm is going broke?

04:52.210 --> 04:54.380
But that was two days ago.
Things have changed.

04:54.420 --> 04:55.780
How?

04:55.790 --> 04:58.380
We are broke.

04:58.860 --> 04:59.790
When you
say broke—

04:59.830 --> 05:03.430
Crane, Poole & Schmidt is bankrupt.
We have no money. Nada. Zilch.

05:03.470 --> 05:05.070
We're busted.

05:05.100 --> 05:07.260
I'll call Congress. They'll bail
us out. After all, we're rich.

05:07.300 --> 05:08.790
I know Hank Paulson. Nutty guy.

05:08.830 --> 05:11.910
–Hey, that's mine.
–It's over, Edwin.

05:13.940 --> 05:16.350
We're done.

05:31.060 --> 05:33.760
I don't know what else to
tell you, Edwin, other than—

05:33.800 --> 05:35.540
You can tell me how it happened.

05:35.580 --> 05:39.550
We had investments in the market, we had
massive receivables from banking industries,

05:39.590 --> 05:41.750
we had to take write-offs.

05:41.760 --> 05:45.550
You just beat the tobacco
companies for millions of dollars.

05:45.590 --> 05:48.130
You think we'll ever
see a penny from that?

05:48.170 --> 05:52.460
After all the appeals, that
victory's going to end up costing us.

05:53.300 --> 05:55.760
Edwin…

05:55.800 --> 05:59.480
we may have to shut our doors.

06:02.960 --> 06:04.820
Do people know?

06:04.840 --> 06:07.680
Only a certain few at this point.

06:07.690 --> 06:10.080
So we're really done, then?

06:10.110 --> 06:12.190
Canceled?

06:12.200 --> 06:14.570
Carl may have overstated that.

06:14.580 --> 06:19.730
There are some possibilities.
I still have hope.

06:23.460 --> 06:26.790
I really thought I'd make it back.

06:26.990 --> 06:29.440
I was getting better and, uh…

06:37.450 --> 06:39.180
Listen, I bought a turkey.

06:39.200 --> 06:43.010
I'd love to have you over for thanksgiving on
Thursday, maybe talk about old times and, uh—

06:43.050 --> 06:46.070
Edwin, thank you. Um, I have plans.

06:46.080 --> 06:49.650
I'm hosting a little thing at my house.

06:50.090 --> 06:53.420
So I'll come to your house, then?

06:58.030 --> 06:59.040
Edwin Poole?

06:59.050 --> 07:01.380
Well, he kind of
invited himself. I—

07:01.420 --> 07:03.070
We were supposed to have a quiet dinner.

07:03.110 --> 07:04.140
I know. I'm
sorry. But—

07:04.180 --> 07:05.670
And his little felon?

07:05.680 --> 07:06.910
Well, he could be joining.

07:06.950 --> 07:07.690
Oh, Shirley.

07:07.730 --> 07:10.710
I know. I wanted a quiet
evening, too. But somehow—

07:10.750 --> 07:13.140
he had no place to go.
Wh-what was I going to say?

07:13.180 --> 07:15.340
Uh, “no” comes to mind. How about “no”?

07:15.380 --> 07:16.110
Carl.

07:16.120 --> 07:18.820
A nice quiet Thanksgiving
dinner, just the two of us—

07:18.860 --> 07:19.790
that's how you billed it.

07:19.830 --> 07:20.860
And how I wanted it—

07:20.900 --> 07:23.590
Shirley, I've got the
research on the McClean—

07:23.630 --> 07:24.830
I thought you'd gone to London.

07:24.870 --> 07:29.640
Oh, yes, I was planning to, but the airline
screwed up with the tickets. It's a long story.

07:29.680 --> 07:32.530
So suffice to say, I'll be staying put.

07:32.550 --> 07:35.410
Oh, well, that's too bad.

07:35.420 --> 07:39.080
I'm having a few people over.
Why don't you come to my house?

07:39.120 --> 07:40.820
Oh, I wouldn't want to put you out.

07:40.860 --> 07:42.680
It wouldn't be any trouble.

07:42.710 --> 07:44.470
Oh, well, sure. I'd quite love that.

07:44.510 --> 07:46.380
–Great. 1:00, then.
–Splendid.

07:46.420 --> 07:49.360
Oh, w-would it be possible
for me to bring Jerry?

07:49.400 --> 07:52.200
I sort of —when I thought
that I didn't have plans—

07:52.240 --> 07:54.160
Jerry would be more than welcome.

07:54.200 --> 07:57.390
Thank you. I'll go tell him.

07:58.060 --> 07:59.040
Sorry.

07:59.050 --> 08:01.020
The idea of spending
a day alone with me—

08:01.060 --> 08:02.210
you just can't bear it, can you?

08:02.250 --> 08:04.400
Oh, you know that's not true.

08:04.420 --> 08:08.670
Can't we just look at this as a
gathering of a big, dysfunctional family?

08:08.710 --> 08:11.260
Can we do that?

08:11.520 --> 08:15.000
–What about us?
–We can be dysfunctional.

08:28.470 --> 08:31.520
–There.
–Thank you.

08:31.530 --> 08:34.350
–Are you okay?
–Yeah, I'm—I'm fine. I…

08:34.360 --> 08:37.010
just tend to get a little
stressed when I host parties.

08:37.049 --> 08:38.260
Do you not remember?

08:38.299 --> 08:39.830
But this is just a dinner.

08:39.870 --> 08:43.350
It is a Thanksgiving dinner, and let's
face it, with this particular group,

08:43.390 --> 08:47.620
the possibilities for catastrophe—
–What?

08:47.630 --> 08:51.970
Oh, hey, what… We're off
to a good start. Come on.

08:54.950 --> 08:56.930
Surprise.

08:56.940 --> 08:57.890
Hey, Turnip beat you to it.

08:57.930 --> 08:59.750
What were you doing,
staring in my window?

08:59.790 --> 09:02.320
Is this how it's gonna be,
dump-on-Turnip day?

09:02.360 --> 09:05.230
Ah, Turnip, hi. I'm Mr Sack.
I've heard a lot about you.

09:05.270 --> 09:07.000
Hands on the wall.
–Oh, come on.

09:07.040 --> 09:09.060
Now, now, don't worry.
I do this to everybody.

09:09.100 --> 09:10.920
Yeah, try not to enjoy yourself, pops.

09:10.960 --> 09:13.570
–Oh, come on.
–Hello. Welcome. Hello.

09:13.580 --> 09:15.960
Mr Poole.

09:16.120 --> 09:17.060
Thank you, Carl.

09:17.100 --> 09:19.630
–Oh, what a beautiful home.
–Oh, thank you very much.

09:19.670 --> 09:22.330
–Is it all paid for?
–Turnip.

09:22.340 --> 09:25.120
–Not a bad question, actually, considering—
–Edwin.

09:25.160 --> 09:27.290
Here, give me your coats.

09:27.300 --> 09:29.020
Here. Let me take those.

09:29.030 --> 09:30.010
Hey, are we late?

09:30.050 --> 09:32.220
–No, you're just perfectly on time.
–Happy Thanksgiving.

09:32.260 --> 09:33.770
Thank you so much, Alan.

09:33.810 --> 09:35.920
Oh, Edwin.
When did they let you out?

09:35.960 --> 09:38.770
They didn't.

09:39.230 --> 09:42.310
–Uh, well, shall we, um, go to the table?
–Already?

09:42.350 --> 09:43.410
What happened—
–We just got here.

09:43.450 --> 09:46.050
To small talk and mingling and picking
at the turkey when nobody's looking?

09:46.090 --> 09:47.100
Just be quiet, Turnip.

09:47.140 --> 09:48.590
I don't think I can get through this.

09:48.630 --> 09:51.260
You will get through this.

09:53.430 --> 09:55.760
Time-out.

09:57.040 --> 10:00.120
The—the food is hot, and,
um, the table is set, so—

10:00.160 --> 10:02.480
Thank God for GPS.

10:02.490 --> 10:04.550
That's the first thing
I'm gonna be thankful for.

10:04.590 --> 10:06.440
–Hey, how you doing, Jerry?
–You invited him?

10:06.480 --> 10:08.592
Looks like you've eaten already.

10:08.930 --> 10:12.420
You must be Shirley Schmidt. I
googled you, good, that's what I did.

10:12.460 --> 10:14.590
You need to update your headshot.

10:14.630 --> 10:16.130
Who's the little guy?
–Edwin Poole.

10:16.170 --> 10:17.990
Melvin Palmer. How
are we doing, sport?

10:18.030 --> 10:19.890
Don't touch me.

10:19.900 --> 10:22.180
Hey, I didn't get my hug
yet, that's what I didn't get.

10:22.220 --> 10:25.510
I'll start with you, Al, you
big hoot. Come here! Oh, man!

10:25.550 --> 10:27.870
This is like old home week,
that's what this is like.

10:27.910 --> 10:30.020
Get in here, Denny.

10:30.190 --> 10:32.610
Thanks, Denny.

10:48.000 --> 10:53.140
All right, now look, it's probably
a good thing, whoever that person is.

10:53.180 --> 10:54.250
Why is it a good thing?

10:54.290 --> 10:56.460
He seems like a bit of an ice breaker.

10:56.500 --> 10:59.020
Ice breaker? The man
could've saved the “Titanic.”

10:59.060 --> 11:00.710
Who the hell is that guy?

11:00.720 --> 11:02.560
Listen, you said you like
a little noise and chaos.

11:02.600 --> 11:04.020
Seems he'll be able
to contribute to that.

11:04.060 --> 11:06.410
Oh, this is gonna be such a disaster.

11:06.450 --> 11:08.740
It's not going to be a disaster.

11:08.760 --> 11:10.560
All right, look, I'm gonna go
out there, I'll get everybody,

11:10.600 --> 11:13.530
I'll get them to the table you
take a second to collect yourself,

11:13.570 --> 11:16.280
then come in, all right?

11:16.290 --> 11:19.720
It's gonna be great. It's
gonna be a splendid day.

11:37.710 --> 11:39.540
–Okay.
–Good idea. Let's drink.

11:39.580 --> 11:44.430
Uh, D-Denny, I just wanted to say
how nice it is to have all of you here.

11:44.440 --> 11:46.110
The food looks positively delicious.

11:46.150 --> 11:47.400
I don't know where to start.

11:47.440 --> 11:50.870
Well, you can start with a moment
of silence, Melvin, or maybe an hour.

11:50.910 --> 11:52.540
Double hoot, that's what you are.

11:52.580 --> 11:53.930
–I'm a double hoot now.
–Perhaps we should pray.

11:53.970 --> 11:56.450
–Yeah, maybe for peace.
–Or start with grace.

11:56.490 --> 11:59.460
–Any volunteers, or shall I—
–I'll say grace.

12:02.200 --> 12:04.530
Okay.

12:05.990 --> 12:06.610
Dear God—

12:06.620 --> 12:09.040
–No, no, no,
–Oh, I think grace was a bad idea.

12:09.080 --> 12:11.480
–Maybe we should skip grace.
–You don't even believe in God. How can you a—

12:11.520 --> 12:13.050
–I do, too.
–A Christian God?

12:13.090 --> 12:14.540
–Does it matter?
–Well, it does to me.

12:14.580 --> 12:16.540
I'm not gonna let you pray
to a Muslim God, not while I—

12:16.580 --> 12:18.180
Why does he have to be
either Christian or Muslim?

12:18.220 --> 12:19.800
He could be Texan,
that's what he could be.

12:19.840 --> 12:22.470
Well, I-I-if he chooses good
over evil, he's Christian.

12:22.510 --> 12:23.740
Why couldn't he be Jewish?

12:23.780 --> 12:26.110
Are you nuts?

12:27.720 --> 12:30.290
I am not giving thanks to
a Jewish God, a Muslim God.

12:30.330 --> 12:31.880
Hindu maybe, 'cause
they love sheep.

12:31.920 --> 12:32.860
–Jew hater.
–What?

12:32.900 --> 12:34.030
–Edwin, Edwin—
–Jew hater.

12:34.070 --> 12:37.970
Enough, enough. Let's
skip grace and let's eat.

12:37.980 --> 12:42.310
And if it's not too much trouble, I'd like to
have a nice Thanksgiving dinner with no fights.

12:42.350 --> 12:44.610
Can we do that, please?

12:44.620 --> 12:47.430
I'm positively famished.

12:50.450 --> 12:52.500
Thank you.

12:53.590 --> 12:56.580
So, Turnip, tell me, what do
little black kids like to eat?

12:56.620 --> 13:00.070
–Oh, for God's sake, Denny.
–What do black kids like to eat?

13:00.110 --> 13:01.050
Well, I want to know.

13:01.090 --> 13:03.820
–Well, how about, “hey, Turnip,
what sort of food do you like?”
–Koreans like korean food. Greeks like greek food.

13:03.860 --> 13:05.830
Feisty bunch.

13:05.970 --> 13:08.050
–Racist?
–Yes, racist. This is a holiday.

13:08.090 --> 13:13.590
Please, let's not extend the systemic
racism of the firm to the dining room table.

13:15.720 --> 13:18.800
What systemic racism of the firm?

13:18.830 --> 13:19.950
Oh, come on, Shirley.

13:19.990 --> 13:22.200
No, I'd like to hear this.

13:22.230 --> 13:24.130
Well, look around the
table or the office.

13:24.170 --> 13:25.050
You see any black attorneys?

13:25.090 --> 13:27.880
–It doesn't mean we're racist.
–Right.

13:27.890 --> 13:32.040
Did you ever think for one second that maybe
black attorneys don't want to work with us,

13:32.080 --> 13:33.870
maybe they want to be with their own?

13:33.910 --> 13:35.280
Denny, don't help me, please.

13:35.320 --> 13:37.150
–Could you please pass the—
–No!

13:37.190 --> 13:40.090
We just had a black man elected
president, and you still think—

13:40.130 --> 13:42.390
–Oh, please.
–What, “oh, please”?

13:42.400 --> 13:43.780
–Never mind.
–No, say it.

13:43.820 --> 13:45.250
I-I want to hear this, Alan.

13:45.290 --> 13:46.380
–I-I don't.
–Neither do I.

13:46.420 --> 13:51.180
I do. Say it, Alan. I want
to hear what you have to say.

13:51.190 --> 13:53.410
What, you really think
we've turned the corner?

13:53.450 --> 13:56.710
Of a hundred senators, one is
black, one, and that's Barack Obama.

13:56.750 --> 13:58.600
Come January, there'll be none.

13:58.640 --> 14:02.260
Of 50 governors, 2 are black, and
one of those is in New York, uh,

14:02.300 --> 14:04.470
by default because Eliot Spitzer
got caught with his hooker.

14:04.510 --> 14:08.350
This country hardly seems willing to
elect black leaders on a regular basis.

14:08.390 --> 14:09.700
But the people of this firm are.

14:09.740 --> 14:11.510
They voted overwhelmingly for Obama.

14:11.550 --> 14:14.850
How do you know what the hell went on in
the privacy of all those voting booths?

14:14.890 --> 14:16.930
Get out of this house.

14:16.940 --> 14:18.090
I haven't even eaten yet.

14:18.130 --> 14:19.850
I don't care.

14:19.860 --> 14:23.226
–He will not say things like that—
–What did I say?

14:24.650 --> 14:27.910
Maybe since Barack
Obama w-was just elected,

14:27.950 --> 14:29.920
we could celebrate the progress that blacks
have made in this country instead of—

14:29.960 --> 14:31.160
Celebrate?

14:31.170 --> 14:35.550
In America, black people are incarcerated
at almost six times the rate of white people.

14:35.590 --> 14:38.040
Turnip here seems already
to be well on his way—

14:38.080 --> 14:42.490
Blacks have double the unemployment rate
of whites and have for over 40 years.

14:42.530 --> 14:46.030
Whether it's that or the government's
underwhelming response to AIDS

14:46.070 --> 14:50.150
among blacks or racial profiling, the black
community continues to get screwed.

14:50.190 --> 14:54.290
Let's not even discuss, os uh, funding for
public schools in black neighborhoods

14:54.330 --> 14:57.780
or our supreme court eviscerating
Brown vs Board of Education.

14:57.820 --> 15:02.310
We've got that, uh, republican congressman
uh, Lynn Westmoreland from Georgia,

15:02.350 --> 15:06.510
who referred to Obama as “uppity”
—not once, twice— “uppity.”

15:06.520 --> 15:10.280
